The paper deals with geometric graphs and wireless sensor networks, which are typical topics in computational geometry (cs.CG) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The focus on matchings and blocking sets suggests that the paper may also be relevant to combinatorial optimization (cs.DS) and information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the use of theta-six graphs, which are a specific type of geometric graph, further supports the likelihood of cs.CG being the most relevant sub-category.
